<paragraph blockId="1.[151,487,1214,1240]" box="[151,487,1214,1240]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,487,1214,1240]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,487,1214,1240]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1918" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1918" box="[238,487,1214,1240]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Calvarium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[238,367,1214,1240]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Calvarium</emphasis>
Pic, 
<number box="[428,487,1214,1240]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1918.0">1918</number>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1285,1490]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
The genus 
<emphasis box="[279,427,1285,1309]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<taxonomicName box="[279,399,1285,1309]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Calvarium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Calvarium</taxonomicName>
w
</emphasis>
as proposed for non-saltatorial African 
<taxonomicName box="[881,981,1285,1310]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Scirtidae</taxonomicName>
with unmodified hind legs. The poorly known genus was redescribed by Ruta (
<number box="[609,671,1322,1346]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="2010.0">2010</number>
). He transferred several species first described in genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1318,1405,1321,1345]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Cyphon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1318,1405,1321,1345]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Cyphon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName box="[151,271,1357,1381]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Calvarium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,271,1357,1381]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Calvarium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and provided a list of the named species, many of them Asian. The genus is for the first time recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[212,318,1393,1418]" name="Australia" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Australia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1285,1490]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
The six new Australian species agree with the redescription of 
<taxonomicName authority="Ruta 2010" authorityName="Ruta" authorityYear="2010" box="[900,1161,1429,1454]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Calvarium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[900,1020,1429,1453]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Calvarium</emphasis>
(Ruta 
<number box="[1095,1153,1430,1454]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="2010.0">2010</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
in the following derived characters:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1537,2033]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
• A wide short head with a narrow oral area, the labrum corresponding to only 
<emphasis box="[1062,1089,1538,1561]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">ca</emphasis>
<number box="[1096,1125,1538,1562]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="20.0">20</number>
% of total head width (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1 − 9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1883,1906]" captionTargetBox="[179,1406,213,1835]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[173,1417,195,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 − 9. Calvarium spp., head morphology. 1 – 5, C. (C.) australiense, n. sp.; 6 – 9, C. (Calvariellum) hamifer, n. sp.: 1, 6, ventral views of mounted heads; 2, left mandible, dorsal view; 3, labrum; 4, maxillary palpus; 5, labium; 7, frontal view, slightly from ventral side, diagrammatic, right antenna removed; 8, maxillary palpus; 9, labial palpus. Figures 2 – 5 and 8, 9 to the same scale, respectively; Fig. 7 not to scale. Abbreviations: af, antennal foramen; as, accessory suture; asu, antennal sulcus; la, labrum; md, mandible; sgr, subgenal ridge; sor, subocular ridge; trs, transverse suture." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286793/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Figs. 1, 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1537,2033]" box="[151,556,1609,1634]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
• A deep antennal sulcus (
<figureCitation box="[473,542,1609,1634]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 − 9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1883,1906]" captionTargetBox="[179,1406,213,1835]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[173,1417,195,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 − 9. Calvarium spp., head morphology. 1 – 5, C. (C.) australiense, n. sp.; 6 – 9, C. (Calvariellum) hamifer, n. sp.: 1, 6, ventral views of mounted heads; 2, left mandible, dorsal view; 3, labrum; 4, maxillary palpus; 5, labium; 7, frontal view, slightly from ventral side, diagrammatic, right antenna removed; 8, maxillary palpus; 9, labial palpus. Figures 2 – 5 and 8, 9 to the same scale, respectively; Fig. 7 not to scale. Abbreviations: af, antennal foramen; as, accessory suture; asu, antennal sulcus; la, labrum; md, mandible; sgr, subgenal ridge; sor, subocular ridge; trs, transverse suture." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286793/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Fig. 
<number box="[526,542,1610,1634]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1537,2033]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
• Antennal scape wide, with sharp anterior edge. At rest it lies horizontally in the space between the antennal insertion and the eye, filling it completely. Pedicel inserted on the lower face of the scape, near its distal edge. The pedicel and the base of the flagellum lie deep in the antennal sulcus when the pedicel stands at right angle to the scape. The tip of the long 
<number box="[449,463,1756,1780]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="2.0">2</number>
nd flagellomere projects caudally from the sulcus (
<figureCitation box="[1020,1088,1756,1781]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 − 9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1883,1906]" captionTargetBox="[179,1406,213,1835]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[173,1417,195,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 − 9. Calvarium spp., head morphology. 1 – 5, C. (C.) australiense, n. sp.; 6 – 9, C. (Calvariellum) hamifer, n. sp.: 1, 6, ventral views of mounted heads; 2, left mandible, dorsal view; 3, labrum; 4, maxillary palpus; 5, labium; 7, frontal view, slightly from ventral side, diagrammatic, right antenna removed; 8, maxillary palpus; 9, labial palpus. Figures 2 – 5 and 8, 9 to the same scale, respectively; Fig. 7 not to scale. Abbreviations: af, antennal foramen; as, accessory suture; asu, antennal sulcus; la, labrum; md, mandible; sgr, subgenal ridge; sor, subocular ridge; trs, transverse suture." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286793/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Fig. 
<number box="[1072,1088,1756,1780]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1537,2033]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
• Prosternal process with anterior portion parallel-sided, posterior portion wide, lanceolate, pilose (
<figureCitation box="[1288,1369,1792,1817]" captionStart="FIGURES 18 − 20" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1825,1848]" captionTargetBox="[248,1335,1100,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[244,1342,1095,1801]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 18 − 20. Calvarium (Calvariellum) hamifer, n. sp., male: 18, contour in dorsal view; 19, antenna; 20, central portion of thorax, ventral side. After photographs. Fig. 20 not to scale, diagrammatic. Abbreviations: cx I, fore coxa; cx II, middle coxa; g, groove receiving prosternal process (psp); msp, process of mesoventrite; mtp, process of metaventrite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286796/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Fig. 
<number box="[1340,1369,1792,1816]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
). • Groove on mesoventrite receiving the prosternal process wide and short, bordered by ridges (
<figureCitation box="[1243,1327,1828,1853]" captionStart="FIGURES 18 − 20" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1825,1848]" captionTargetBox="[248,1335,1100,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[244,1342,1095,1801]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 18 − 20. Calvarium (Calvariellum) hamifer, n. sp., male: 18, contour in dorsal view; 19, antenna; 20, central portion of thorax, ventral side. After photographs. Fig. 20 not to scale, diagrammatic. Abbreviations: cx I, fore coxa; cx II, middle coxa; g, groove receiving prosternal process (psp); msp, process of mesoventrite; mtp, process of metaventrite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286796/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Fig. 
<number box="[1295,1327,1828,1852]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
). • Mesoventrite wide and short, barely longer than distance between middle coxae (
<figureCitation box="[1108,1192,1864,1889]" captionStart="FIGURES 18 − 20" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1825,1848]" captionTargetBox="[248,1335,1100,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[244,1342,1095,1801]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 18 − 20. Calvarium (Calvariellum) hamifer, n. sp., male: 18, contour in dorsal view; 19, antenna; 20, central portion of thorax, ventral side. After photographs. Fig. 20 not to scale, diagrammatic. Abbreviations: cx I, fore coxa; cx II, middle coxa; g, groove receiving prosternal process (psp); msp, process of mesoventrite; mtp, process of metaventrite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286796/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Fig. 
<number box="[1160,1192,1864,1888]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
). • Coarse, groove-like punctures laterally from mesoventral groove and behind front margin of metaventral process (
<figureCitation box="[250,334,1936,1961]" captionStart="FIGURES 18 − 20" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1825,1848]" captionTargetBox="[248,1335,1100,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[244,1342,1095,1801]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 18 − 20. Calvarium (Calvariellum) hamifer, n. sp., male: 18, contour in dorsal view; 19, antenna; 20, central portion of thorax, ventral side. After photographs. Fig. 20 not to scale, diagrammatic. Abbreviations: cx I, fore coxa; cx II, middle coxa; g, groove receiving prosternal process (psp); msp, process of mesoventrite; mtp, process of metaventrite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286796/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Fig. 
<number box="[302,334,1936,1960]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1537,2033]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
The characteristic structure of the described male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[911,1031,1972,1996]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Calvarium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[911,1031,1972,1996]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Calvarium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, including membranous S 
<number box="[1422,1436,1972,1996]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="8.0">8</number>
and S 
<number box="[213,227,2008,2032]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="9.0">9</number>
lacking sclerites (Klausnitzer 
<number box="[569,628,2008,2033]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="2006.0">2006</number>
a, b, Ruta 2007, 2010,Yoshitomi 1998, 2007, Yoshitomi &amp; Sato 
<number box="[1345,1403,2008,2032]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="2004.0">2004</number>
) is shared by only two of the new Australian species, from the Northern Territory (
<figureCitation box="[1075,1214,151,176]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 10 − 13" captionStart-1="FIGURES 14 − 17" captionStartId-0="4.[151,264,1270,1293]" captionStartId-1="5.[151,264,1608,1631]" captionTargetBox-0="[236,1346,204,1245]" captionTargetBox-1="[168,1417,462,1568]" captionTargetId-0="figure@4.[232,1355,195,1247]" captionTargetId-1="figure@5.[151,1436,447,1584]" captionTargetPageId-0="4" captionTargetPageId-1="5" captionText-0="FIGURES 10 − 13. Calvarium (Calvarium) australiense, n. sp., male: 10, T 8; 11, T 9; 12, penis; 13, tegmen and parameres. All to the same scale." captionText-1="FIGURES 14 − 17. Calvarium (Calvarium) superbum, n. sp., male: 14, superimposed T 8 and T 9; 15, tegmen and parameres; 16, penis; 14 – 16 are dorsal views, to the same scale. 17, slightly oblique lateral view of tegmen and parameres overlying the penis; after a photograph of the cleared, artificially everted genitalia, not to scale." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/286794/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/286795/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Figs. 
<number box="[1141,1214,152,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="13.5" valueMax="17.0" valueMin="10.0">10–17</number>
</figureCitation>
). Four new species from North Queensland differ in male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[689,824,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 − 25" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1336,1359]" captionTargetBox="[249,1337,203,1303]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[242,1345,195,1312]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 21 − 25. Calvarium (Calvariellum) hamifer, n. sp., male: 21, T 8, ventral; 22, S 8; 23, S 9 and the apodemes representing T 9, superimposed; 24, penis; 25 tegmen (25 holotype, the other paratypes from Mt. Tozer; all to the same scale)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286797/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Figs. 
<number box="[751,779,188,213]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="21.0">21</number>
–25
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[835,909,188,212]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 29 − 37" captionStart-1="FIGURES 38 − 42" captionStartId-0="10.[151,264,1707,1730]" captionStartId-1="12.[151,264,1706,1729]" captionTargetBox-0="[246,1345,203,1671]" captionTargetBox-1="[244,1342,846,1680]" captionTargetId-0="figure@10.[228,1358,197,1686]" captionTargetId-1="figure@12.[237,1349,842,1683]" captionTargetPageId-0="10" captionTargetPageId-1="12" captionText-0="FIGURES 29 − 37. Calvarium (Calvariellum) spp., males. C. cochlearifer, n. sp.: 29, T 8 and S 8, superimposed; 30, penis; 31, T 9, S 9 and tegmen (tn) with parameres (p) superimposed. C. bellendenker, n. sp.: 32, T 8; 33, S 8; 34, T 9; 35, S 9; 36, penis; 37, tegmen and parameres. Figures for a given species to the same scale." captionText-1="FIGURES 38 − 42. Calvarium (Calvariellum) lancifer, n. sp., male: 38, T 8; 39, detail of microtrichial armature of same; 40, one of the struts representing T 9; 41, S 9 and tegmen (tn) with parameres (p) superimposed; 42, penis. All figures except 39 to the same scale." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/286799/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/286800/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
29– 
<number box="[879,909,188,212]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="42.0">42</number>
</figureCitation>
). The sutures on the lower face of the head also differ somewhat (
<figureCitation box="[354,466,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 − 9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1883,1906]" captionTargetBox="[179,1406,213,1835]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[173,1417,195,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 − 9. Calvarium spp., head morphology. 1 – 5, C. (C.) australiense, n. sp.; 6 – 9, C. (Calvariellum) hamifer, n. sp.: 1, 6, ventral views of mounted heads; 2, left mandible, dorsal view; 3, labrum; 4, maxillary palpus; 5, labium; 7, frontal view, slightly from ventral side, diagrammatic, right antenna removed; 8, maxillary palpus; 9, labial palpus. Figures 2 – 5 and 8, 9 to the same scale, respectively; Fig. 7 not to scale. Abbreviations: af, antennal foramen; as, accessory suture; asu, antennal sulcus; la, labrum; md, mandible; sgr, subgenal ridge; sor, subocular ridge; trs, transverse suture." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286793/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Figs. 1, 6</figureCitation>
). Therefore, a new subgenus, 
<emphasis box="[817,965,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Calvariellum</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[974,1091,223,248]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">n. subgen</emphasis>
., is proposed separating them from the nominate subgenus in which all other species remain.
</paragraph>
